Hey Zack — one option worth exploring before purchasing ELS is using a free Red Hat Developer Account (developers.redhat.com). It gives you access to RHEL and the latest patches at no cost for development/non-production use. The caveat is it's limited to a small number of systems and is technically for dev use only, so it may not be viable for production Apigee VMs depending on your compliance posture.

That said, it could at least be used to test the patching process and validate the upgrade path before committing to ELS licensing.

For production, if ELS is the route, purchasing directly through Red Hat (redhat.com/store) rather than Azure Marketplace is usually more straightforward — especially in govcloud where Marketplace availability can be limited as you noted.

Happy to dig into this further with you and Chris.
